message: The "controversies" part is NOT ABOUT Sabiha Gokcen. It is an attempt by  "Yerevantsi" and "Bagramyan" to write out the claim that Hrant Dink's interview "revealed the racism of Turkish society". This is completely a subjective opinion and off-topic.

/* Early life */ Her origins are not a "matter of dispute". The fabricators of this claim are "Yerevantsi" and "Bagramyan", who go to every Turkish page and "Armenianize" it. They have turned Wikipedia into a chronicle of Armenian chauvinism..
Wikipedia has become a joke thanks to misinformation aimed at dehumanization. I know you'll undo this "KansasBear" because you have no life, keep spreading lies

Changed 'the river originates in Western Armenia' to 'the river originates in Eastern Turkey'; The source of the river is within the internationally recognized borders of Turkey. Wikipedia is supposed to convey accurate information.
/* Need help on the Sabiha Gokcen page */ new section

/* Claims are not absolute fact */ new section

The publication of a single, unsubstantiated interview in Dink's Armenian journal (conveniently) after Sabiha Gokcen's death which was rejected by her family is not grounds to categorically state "her origins are disputed". This is subjective conjecture.
/* Question regarding subjective editing */ new section

Grammatical changes; Armenian users who keep editing the history to say "Kahramanmaras was occupied by the Turkish National Assembly" will be reported. The correct version is that Kahramanmaras was "liberated" from the French occupation.

There are claims that 9/11 was an "inside job". Does the 9/11 page start the history with "the origins of 9/11 are disputed" or does it have a separate "claims section". Same goes for the Armenian Genocide page, and it should be the same here.
Not enough of a basis to state her origins are a matter of dispute. In her own autobiography she clearly states who her parents are, and that she is Turkish. Take it to the talk page
